{
  "slug": "dative-verbs",
  "title": "Verben mit Dativ",
  "level": "A2",
  "explainer_md": "A small group of common verbs takes its object in the **Dativ** — even though English treats it as a direct object. These you simply memorize with the verb.\n\n**The most important ones:** [[helfen]] (help), [[danken]] (thank), [[gefallen]] (please/like), [[gehören]] (belong to), [[antworten]] (answer), [[glauben]] (believe), [[schmecken]] (taste good), [[passen]] (fit), [[gratulieren]] (congratulate), [[folgen]] (follow).\n\n*Ich helfe **dem** Mann.* — I help the man.\n\n*Wir danken **dem** Lehrer.* — We thank the teacher.\n\n*Antwortest du **deinem** Vater?* — Are you answering your father?\n\n**Watch out — three verbs flip the sentence around.** With *gefallen*, *gehören* and *schmecken* the **thing is the subject** and the person is Dativ:\n\n*Der Film gefällt **mir**.* — I like the film. (literally: the film pleases me)\n\n*Das Buch gehört **ihr**.* — The book belongs to her.\n\n*Die Pizza schmeckt **den** Kindern.* — The kids like the pizza.\n\n**Tip:** when you learn one of these verbs, learn it with a pronoun: *hilf **mir***, *es gefällt **mir***, *es gehört **mir*** — then the Dativ comes automatically.",
